Rare tokens: They are kept if they appear in optimal segmentations (Viterbi paths) or contribute enough to likelihood. Low-frequency tokens with no good alternatives are often retained.
Safeguards: Byte fallback (common in modern setups) encodes unseen/rare characters as <0xXX> byte tokens. Special "always keep" logic protects critical pieces (e.g., single characters, specials). Pruning is gradual (e.g., remove 10-20% at a time based on loss impact).
Trade-off: It can yield better probabilistic tokenization than pure frequency-based BPE, but it's more computationally expensive to train. Recent tweaks (e.g., simpler final pruning) trade slight loss for better compression.

